1. Overview¶

Hypothetical Situation:¶

You are a data analyst at the online retail company. The company wants to make a marketing campaign to increase sales and brand awareness at the end of the quarter. But they are on a tight budget so the campaign only targets a handful of customers. They ask you to make use of dataset's company and show them which type of customers should the campaign aims at

Requirement:¶

As a data analyst of team, it is your mission to perform EDA and do Customer Segmentation to help company make a data-informed decision about the campaign

2. Dataset Description¶

Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/imakash3011/customer-personality-analysis
Our hypothetical dataset is from kaggle. It consists of 2240 datapoints and a total of 29 attributes. All the attributes could be divided into sub categories as follows

Customer's Information

  • ID
  • Year_Birth
  • Education
  • Marital_Status
  • Income
  • Kidhome
  • Teenhome
  • Dt_Customer
  • Recency
  • Complain

Products
Amount of money spent on that product in the last 2 years

  • MntWines
  • MntFruits
  • MntMeatProducts
  • MntFishProducts
  • MntSweetProducts
  • MntGoldProds

Place
Number of purchases customers made on each platform

  • NumWebPurchases
  • NumCatalogPurchases
  • NumStorePurchases
  • NumWebVisitsMonth

Promotion
Information about campaigns on each customer. 1 if customer accepted the offer in the nth campaign, 0 otherwise

  • NumDealsPurchases
  • AcceptedCmp1
  • AcceptedCmp2
  • AcceptedCmp3
  • AcceptedCmp4
  • AcceptedCmp5
  • Response

3.2 Handling Outliers¶

In 29 columns, Income is the only numerical column that we need to handle outliers because it will directly affect our clustering analysis.
Use boxplot to detect outliers

In [4]:
df_edited.boxplot('Income')
Out[4]:
<AxesSubplot:>

We can clearly see that the single maximum value of Income (>600000) is an outlier. As a result, we could limit that datapoint to a certain value like 150000 if we have a small dataset, but in this case we can ideally remove it without significant effect on our dataset

In [5]:
df_edited = df_edited.drop(df_edited[df_edited['Income'] > 600000].index)

We now have 2239 rows, it shows that the only outlier has been removed successfully

3.4 Feature Engineering and Data Reduction¶

With nearly 30 columns, we should not try to fit every feature into our cluster analysis model and hope it performs well. So it does make sense for us to extract only essential information from raw data and use it for customer segmentation model

Here is a list of things that we will do for our feature engineering

  • Find age from Year_Birth column and Customer's total day of enrollment
  • Find total of purchases from Place category
  • Find total money spent from Product category and average money per paycheck
  • Find total accepted campaign from Campagin category
  • Split Marital_Status into 2 main sub categories: Single and In relationship
  • Combine Kidhome and Teenhome into only 1 column

Find age from Year_Birth column and Customer's total day of enrollment¶

We subtract Year_Birth from current date to find age of customer (age = CurrentDate - Year_Birth)
We assume the customers's information was reported in the first day of 2015

4. Customer Segmentaion¶

Import needed libraries for cluster analysis model¶

We will use K-Mean algorithm to group similar customers together and discover underlying pattern

In [28]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score
import matplotlib.colors
import random

a. Feature Standardization¶

K-Mean often uses Euclidean Distance to form a group, if we do not standarize before feeding numerical features to ML algorithm then our model will be dominated or heavily biased by a feature with large scale
For example: Income column has larger value than the rest, so it will be dominated in model if we don't perform standarization

In [29]:
sc = StandardScaler()
df_edited=df_edited.select_dtypes(include='number')
df_edited_scaled = pd.DataFrame(sc.fit_transform(df_edited),columns = df_edited.columns,index=df_edited.index)

b. Feature Selection¶

Feature Selection is one of the most important tasks in customer segmentation problem. Different features affect clusters differently, some features are vital for clusters while the others may not be so important as you think

In this section, I will choose features based on several common characteristics of customer like:

  • Demographic: includes personal information such as income, gender, race, nationality, occupation,...
  • Geographic: includes climate, city or country, population density,..
  • Psychographic: includes customers personality and preferences like attitudes, opinions, values, interests, lifestyle and motivations
  • Behavioral: The way a customer behaves affects how they interact with businesses, includes purchasing habits, brand loyalty,..
In [31]:
df_feats=df_edited_scaled[['Income', 'Days_is_customer', 'avg_check']].copy()

Based on 4 characteristics above, I decided to choose Income (Demographic), Days_is_customer (Behavioral), avg_check (Psychographic) columns as features for K-Mean algorithm

c. Find optimal number of clusters by Silhoutte Method¶

The number of clusters plays an important role in customer segmentation, we don't want to have too much (hard to focus) or too little (lack of details) groups of customer
In order to perform well in clustering, we want to minimize the distance between datapoints within a cluster to its centroid (increase compactness of cluster) and there are 2 main techniques that we can help us with that: The elbow method and Silhoutte method. If you want to find out more about these 2 methods, just click the link below
https://vitalflux.com/elbow-method-silhouette-score-which-better/#:~:text=The%20major%20difference%20between%20elbow,high%2Dlow%20differences%2C%20etc.

In [32]:
# Calculate Silhoutte score for each number of clusters
scoreList=[]
n=10
clusterNum=list(range(2,n))
for n_clusters in range(2,n):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters,init = 'k-means++')
    preds = km.fit_predict(df_feats)
    labels=km.labels_
    #centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_

    score = silhouette_score(df_feats, preds)
    scoreList.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {})".format(n_clusters, round(score,3)))

For n_clusters = 2, silhouette score is 0.357)
For n_clusters = 3, silhouette score is 0.31)
For n_clusters = 4, silhouette score is 0.317)
For n_clusters = 5, silhouette score is 0.321)
For n_clusters = 6, silhouette score is 0.298)
For n_clusters = 7, silhouette score is 0.299)
For n_clusters = 8, silhouette score is 0.289)
For n_clusters = 9, silhouette score is 0.285)

plt.plot(clusterNum,scoreList)

Out[33]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Silhoustte score')

For the above-given graph, the optimal value for cluster would be any number between 2 to 5. As we can see after 5, the more cluster you add the less Silhoutte score you would get. Furthermore, 2 to 5 clusters would be the ideal number for groups of customer

def addlabels(x,y):
    total=sum(y)
    for i in range(len(x)):
        myStr=str(y[i])+' | '+str(round(y[i]*100/total,1))+'%'
        plt.text(i,y[i]//2,myStr,ha = 'center')

def createRandomColor(n):
    number_of_colors  = ["#"+''.join([random.choice('0123456789ABCDEF') for j in range(6)])
             for i in range(n)]
    return number_of_colors
colors=createRandomColor(4)
